 of computation]]\n[[Category:Computability theory]]\n[[Category:Gottfried Leibniz]]\n[[Category:Mathematical logic]]\n[[Category:Metatheorems]]\n[[Category:Undecidable problems]]\n", "name_user": "GreenHat99", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Entscheidungsproblem"}
{"title_page": "7th Pennsylvania Reserve Regiment", "text_new": "{{short description|Union Army infantry regiment}}\nThe '''7th Pennsylvania Reserve Regiment''', also known as the '''36th Regiment Pennsylvania Volunteer Infantry''', was a regiment in the [[Union Army]] during the [[American Civil War]]. It formed part of the [[Pennsylvania Reserves|Pennsylvania Reserve division]] in the [[Army of the Potomac]] for most of the war. The regiment served in a number of important battles throughout the [[Eastern Theater of the American Civil War|Eastern Theater]], including [[Battle of Antietam|Antietam]] and [[Battle of Fredericksburg|Fredericksburg]].{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name= 7th Pennsylvania Reserve Regiment\n| image=Flag of Pennsylvania.svg\n| image_size = 100\n|caption=Pennsylvania flag\n|dates= June 6, 1861, to June 16, 1864\n|country= [[United States]]\n|allegiance= [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]]\n|branch= [[Infantry]]\n|equipment=\n<!-- Culture and history -->\n|battles=[[Battle of Mechanicsville]]<br/>[[Battle of Gaines' Mill]]<br/>[[Battle of Glendale]]<br/>[[Battle of Malvern Hill]]<br/>[[Battle of Second Bull Run]]<br/>[[Battle of South Mountain]]<br/>[[Battle of Antietam]]<br/>[[Battle of Fredericksburg]]<br/>[[Battle of the Wilderness]]<br/>[[Battle of Laurel Hill]]<br/>[[Battle of Spottsylvania Court House]]<br/>[[Battle of North Anna]]<br/>[[Battle of Totopotomoy Creek]]}}\n\n\n==Organization==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Company !! Moniker !! Primary Location of Recruitment !! Captains\n|-\n| A || The Carlilse Fencibles || [[Cumberland County, Pennsylvania|Cumberland County]] || R.M. Henderson\n|-\n| B || The Biddle Rifles || [[Perry County, Pennsylvania|Perry County]] || John Jameson\n|-\n| C || The Iron Artillery || [[Lebanon County, Pennsylvania|Lebanon County]] || E.G. Lantz\n|-\n| D || The Rifle Guards || [[Clinton County, Pennsylvania|Clinton County]] || Chauncy A. Lyman\n|-\n| E || The Ridgway Guards || [[Philadelphia]] || Chas. S. Peall\n|-\n| F || The Wyoming Bank Infantry || [[Luzerne County, Pennsylvania|Luzerne County]] || Elisha B. Harvey\n|-\n| G || The Second Philadelphia Guards || Philadelphia || John G. Chapman\n|-\n| H || The Cumberland Guards || Cumberland County || Joseph Totten\n|-\n| I || The Myerstown Rifles || Lebanon County || Jerome Myers\n|-\n| K || The Douglas Guards || Philadelphia || Casper Martino{{sfn|Sypher|1865|p=84}}\n|}\n\n==Service==\nThe 7th Pennsylvania Reserves were organized at [[Camp Curtin]] in [[Harrisburg, Pennsylvania]].  They were ordered to [[Washington D.C.]] on July 21st and mustered into United States service July 27, 1861.{{sfn|Dyer|1908|p=1580}}  Elisha B. Harvey, of [[Wilkes-Barre, Pennsylvania]], served as the regiment's first [[colonel]], Joseph Totten as [[lieutenant colonel]] and Chauncey A. Lyman as [[major]]. It was sent to [[Washington, D.C.]], where the [[division (military)|division]] was assigned to the [[I Corps (ACW)|I Corps]] of the [[Army of the Potomac]]. The I Corps remained in northern [[Virginia]] instead of following the rest of the Army for the [[Peninsula Campaign]] in 1862. In May, due to [[Major General|Maj. Gen.]] [[George B. McClellan]]'s demands for reinforcements, the division was sent the [[Peninsula Campaign|Peninsula]] as well.\n\nIn August 1862, the [[Army of the Potomac]] was transferred to northern Virginia to support the [[Army of Virginia]]. The 7th Pennsylvania Reserves then fought at Turner's Gap in the [[Battle of South Mountain]], at the [[Battle of Antietam]], and at the [[Battle of Fredericksburg]] on December 12. The Seventh Reserves distinguished themselves at Fredericksburg by capturing over 100 of the enemy, along with the battle flag of the [[Nineteenth Georgia Infantry]], the only trophy seized during the battle.<ref name=PAroots>{{cite web |title=7th Pennsylvania Reserves/36th Pennsylvania Volunteers |url=http://www.pa-roots.com/pacw/reserves/7thres/7hresorg.html |website=www.pa-roots.com |accessdate=21 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[Battle of the Wilderness]], on May 5, 1864, the entire regiment\u2014except for Company B -- found itself hopelessly surrounded by Confederate troops, and was compelled to surrender. 272 officers and men were captured, and were immediately marched to the rear of the rebel army at [[Orange County, Virginia|Orange Court House]], and thence to [[Lynchburg, Virginia]]. The enlisted men were speedily conveyed to the infamous rebel prison pen at [[Andersonville National Historic Site|Andersonville, Georgia]], and the officers were sent to Camp Oglethorpe in [[Macon, Georgia]], and were subsequently placed under fire of Union guns at [[Charleston, South Carolina|Charleston]], for the protection of the city. The prisoners were held until the end of the conflict was near, with some being paroled, and some liberated by Union troops, but with many enlisted dying from starvation, disease and exposure in the period leading up to release.\n\nThe regiment was mustered out on June 16, 1864.{{sfn|Dyer|1908|p=1580}}\n\n==Casualties==\nThe 7th Pennsylvania Reserves lost 3 officers and 80 enlisted men killed and mortally wounded in battle, and 135 enlisted men dead for reasons not directly caused in action (disease, etc.) -- 67 of these at Andersonville, and an undetermined number after the captives were moved to [[Florence Stockade|Florence, South Carolina]], totalling 218 fatalities.<ref name=PAroots/><ref>{{cite web |title=Union Regiments - Pennsylvania |url=http://www.civilwararchive.com/unionpa.htm |website=www.civilwararchive.com |accessdate=21 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Commanders==\n* Col. Elisha B. Harvey, June 26, 1861, to July 4, 1862 (resigned)\n* Col. Henry C. Bolinger (Capt. of Company D 6/26/1861, to Lt. Col. 5/5/1862, then Col. 8/1/1862; captured at the Wilderness, May 5, 1864; sent to Macon, GA)\n* Capt. Samuel B. King (of Company H), May 1864 to June 16, 1864 (mustered out)\n\n==See also==\n*[[Pennsylvania Reserves]]\n*[[Pennsylvania in the Civil War]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Dyer\n  | first = Frederick H.\n  | year = 1908\n  | title = A Compendium of the War of the Rebellion\n  | publisher = Dyer Pub. Co.\n  | ref = harv\n  | url = https://archive.org/details/08697590.3359.emory.edu\n}}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Sypher\n  | first = Josiah Rhinehart\n  | year = 1865\n  | title = History of the Pennsylvania Reserves: A Complete Record of the Organization\n  | publisher = Elias Barr & Co.\n  | ref = harv\n  | url = https://archive.org/details/historypennsylv00esqgoog\n}}\n;Attribution\n*{{CWR}}\n*[http://www.civilwararchive.com/unionpa.htm The Civil War Archive]\n*[http://www.pa-roots.com/pacw/reserves/7thres/7hresorg.html Pennsylvania in the Civil War]\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.pareserves.com The Pennsylvania Reserve Volunteer Corps Historical Society]\n\n[[Category:Pennsylvania Civil War regiments]]\n[[Category:Pennsylvania Reserves]]\n[[Category:1861 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1861]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations disestablished in 1864]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Union Army infantry regiment}}\nThe '''7th Pennsylvania Reserve Regiment''', also known as the 36th Pennsylvania Volunteer Infantry, was a regiment in the [[Union Army]] during the [[American Civil War]]. It formed part of the [[Pennsylvania Reserves|Pennsylvania Reserve division]] in the [[Army of the Potomac]] for most of the war. The regiment served in a number of important battles throughout the [[Eastern Theater of the American Civil War|Eastern Theater]], including [[Battle of Antietam|Antietam]] and [[Battle of Fredericksburg|Fredericksburg]].{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name= 7th Pennsylvania Reserve Regiment\n| image=Flag of Pennsylvania.svg\n| image_size = 100\n|caption=Pennsylvania flag\n|dates= June 6, 1861, to June 16, 1864\n|country= [[United States]]\n|allegiance= [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]]\n|branch= [[Infantry]]\n|equipment=\n<!-- Culture and history -->\n|battles=[[Battle of Mechanicsville]]<br/>[[Battle of Gaines' Mill]]<br/>[[Battle of Glendale]]<br/>[[Battle of Malvern Hill]]<br/>[[Battle of Second Bull Run]]<br/>[[Battle of South Mountain]]<br/>[[Battle of Antietam]]<br/>[[Battle of Fredericksburg]]<br/>[[Battle of the Wilderness]]<br/>[[Battle of Laurel Hill]]<br/>[[Battle of Spottsylvania Court House]]<br/>[[Battle of North Anna]]<br/>[[Battle of Totopotomoy Creek]]}}\n\n\n==Organization==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Company !! Moniker !! Primary Location of Recruitment !! Captains\n|-\n| A || The Carlilse Fencibles || [[Cumberland County, Pennsylvania|Cumberland County]] || R.M. Henderson\n|-\n| B || The Biddle Rifles || [[Perry County, Pennsylvania|Perry County]] || John Jameson\n|-\n| C || The Iron Artillery || [[Lebanon County, Pennsylvania|Lebanon County]] || E.G. Lantz\n|-\n| D || The Rifle Guards || [[Clinton County, Pennsylvania|Clinton County]] || Chauncy A. Lyman\n|-\n| E || The Ridgway Guards || [[Philadelphia]] || Chas. S. Peall\n|-\n| F || The Wyoming Bank Infantry || [[Luzerne County, Pennsylvania|Luzerne County]] || Elisha B. Harvey\n|-\n| G || The Second Philadelphia Guards || Philadelphia || John G. Chapman\n|-\n| H || The Cumberland Guards || Cumberland County || Joseph Totten\n|-\n| I || The Myerstown Rifles || Lebanon County || Jerome Myers\n|-\n| K || The Douglas Guards || Philadelphia || Casper Martino{{sfn|Sypher|1865|p=84}}\n|}\n\n==Service==\nThe 7th Pennsylvania Reserves were organized at [[Camp Curtin]] in [[Harrisburg, Pennsylvania]].  They were ordered to [[Washington D.C.]] on July 21st and mustered into United States service July 27, 1861.{{sfn|Dyer|1908|p=1580}}  Elisha B. Harvey, of [[Wilkes-Barre, Pennsylvania]], served as the regiment's first [[colonel]], Joseph Totten as [[lieutenant colonel]] and Chauncey A. Lyman as [[major]]. It was sent to [[Washington, D.C.]], where the [[division (military)|division]] was assigned to the [[I Corps (ACW)|I Corps]] of the [[Army of the Potomac]]. The I Corps remained in northern [[Virginia]] instead of following the rest of the Army for the [[Peninsula Campaign]] in 1862. In May, due to [[Major General|Maj. Gen.]] [[George B. McClellan]]'s demands for reinforcements, the division was sent the [[Peninsula Campaign|Peninsula]] as well.\n\nIn August 1862, the [[Army of the Potomac]] was transferred to northern Virginia to support the [[Army of Virginia]]. The 7th Pennsylvania Reserves then fought at Turner's Gap in the [[Battle of South Mountain]], at the [[Battle of Antietam]], and at the [[Battle of Fredericksburg]] on December 12. The Seventh Reserves distinguished themselves at Fredericksburg by capturing over 100 of the enemy, along with the battle flag of the [[Nineteenth Georgia Infantry]], the only trophy seized during the battle.<ref name=PAroots>{{cite web |title=7th Pennsylvania Reserves/36th Pennsylvania Volunteers |url=http://www.pa-roots.com/pacw/reserves/7thres/7hresorg.html |website=www.pa-roots.com |accessdate=21 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[Battle of the Wilderness]], on May 5, 1864, the entire regiment\u2014except for Company B -- found itself hopelessly surrounded by Confederate troops, and was compelled to surrender. 272 officers and men were captured, and were immediately marched to the rear of the rebel army at [[Orange County, Virginia|Orange Court House]], and thence to [[Lynchburg, Virginia]]. The enlisted men were speedily conveyed to the infamous rebel prison pen at [[Andersonville National Historic Site|Andersonville, Georgia]], and the officers were sent to Camp Oglethorpe in [[Macon, Georgia]], and were subsequently placed under fire of Union guns at [[Charleston, South Carolina|Charleston]], for the protection of the city. The prisoners were held until the end of the conflict was near, with some being paroled, and some liberated by Union troops, but with many enlisted dying from starvation, disease and exposure in the period leading up to release.\n\nThe regiment was mustered out on June 16, 1864.{{sfn|Dyer|1908|p=1580}}\n\n==Casualties==\nThe 7th Pennsylvania Reserves lost 3 officers and 80 enlisted men killed and mortally wounded in battle, and 135 enlisted men dead for reasons not directly caused in action (disease, etc.) -- 67 of these at Andersonville, and an undetermined number after the captives were moved to [[Florence Stockade|Florence, South Carolina]], totalling 218 fatalities.<ref name=PAroots/><ref>{{cite web |title=Union Regiments - Pennsylvania |url=http://www.civilwararchive.com/unionpa.htm |website=www.civilwararchive.com |accessdate=21 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Commanders==\n* Col. Elisha B. Harvey, June 26, 1861, to July 4, 1862 (resigned)\n* Col. Henry C. Bolinger (Capt. of Company D 6/26/1861, to Lt. Col. 5/5/1862, then Col. 8/1/1862; captured at the Wilderness, May 5, 1864; sent to Macon, GA)\n* Capt. Samuel B. King (of Company H), May 1864 to June 16, 1864 (mustered out)\n\n==See also==\n*[[Pennsylvania Reserves]]\n*[[Pennsylvania in the Civil War]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Dyer\n  | first = Frederick H.\n  | year = 1908\n  | title = A Compendium of the War of the Rebellion\n  | publisher = Dyer Pub. Co.\n  | ref = harv\n  | url = https://archive.org/details/08697590.3359.emory.edu\n}}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Sypher\n  | first = Josiah Rhinehart\n  | year = 1865\n  | title = History of the Pennsylvania Reserves: A Complete Record of the Organization\n  | publisher = Elias Barr & Co.\n  | ref = harv\n  | url = https://archive.org/details/historypennsylv00esqgoog\n}}\n;Attribution\n*{{CWR}}\n*[http://www.civilwararchive.com/unionpa.htm The Civil War Archive]\n*[http://www.pa-roots.com/pacw/reserves/7thres/7hresorg.html Pennsylvania in the Civil War]\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.pareserves.com The Pennsylvania Reserve Volunteer Corps Historical Society]\n\n[[Category:Pennsylvania Civil War regiments]]\n[[Category:Pennsylvania Reserves]]\n[[Category:1861 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1861]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations disestablished in 1864]]\n", "name_user": "Hhfjbaker", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/7th_Pennsylvania_Reserve_Regiment"}
{"title_page": "List of Parliamentary constituencies in Wiltshire", "text_new": "The [[ceremonial county]] of '''[[Wiltshire]]''', England, (which includes the [[unitary authority]] of [[Borough of Swindon|Swindon]]), is divided into seven [[United Kingdom constituencies|Parliamentary constituencies]]. They are all [[County constituency|County constituencies]].\n\n==Constituencies==\n{{legend2|{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}|[[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]|border=1px solid #aaaaaa}}\n{{legend2|{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}|[[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]|border=1px solid #aaaaaa}}\n{{legend2|{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}|[[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]]|border=1px solid #aaaaaa}}\n\n<!--All columns are for the 2019 election. See [[Parliamentary constituencies in Hertfordshire]] if you have trouble with the \"Member of Parliament\" and \"Nearest opposition\" columns.-->\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!rowspan=1|Constituency<ref group=nb>BC denotes borough constituency, CC denotes county constituency.</ref>\n!rowspan=1|Electorate\n!rowspan=1|Majority<ref group=nb>The majority is the number of votes the winning candidate receives more than their nearest rival.</ref>\n!colspan=2 class=unsortable|[[Member of Parliament]]\n!colspan=2 class=unsortable|Nearest opposition\n<!--!rowspan=1 class=unsortable|Electoral wards<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/si/si2007/uksi_20071681_en_4|title=The Parliamentary Constituencies (England) Order 2007, page 4|publisher=Crown copyright|work=[[Office of Public Sector Information]]|accessdate=7 November 2009|date=13 June 2007}}</ref><ref>[[Boundary Commissions (United Kingdom)|Boundary Commission for England]] pp. 1004\u20131007</ref> -->\n!rowspan=1 class=unsortable|Map\n|-\n|[[Chippenham (UK Parliament constituency)|Chippenham CC]]\n|76,432\n|11,288\n| bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |&nbsp;\n|[[Michelle Donelan]]\n| bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\" 